Conduct an analysis on whether life expectancy is increasing over time.

Code 
# visualize life expectance over time
df %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=lifeExp, color=continent)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.01)+
  geom_smooth()+
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(
    title="Life Expectancy Over time",
    x='year',
    y='Life Expectancy'
    
  )

Run a linear regression on the data with gdpPercap and continent as covariates.

Code 
model1 <- lm(lifeExp ~ gdpPercap + continent, data = df)

Plot the observed trends however you see fit.

Code 
# plot GDP and life expectancy
df %>% ggplot(
  aes(x=log(gdpPercap), y = lifeExp, color = continent)) +
  geom_point()+
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(
    title='life expectancy vs GDP log',
    x='log gdp',
    y='life expectancy'
  )

Code 
df %>% ggplot(
  aes(x=gdpPercap, y = lifeExp, color = continent)) +
  geom_point()+

Followup questions:

  • Write a sentence or two describing the trends you see in the plots. Which model (log or not) did you choose and why?

log, because plot is less clusters with log(gdp)

  • Write a sentence or two to explain the coefficients on your linear model output, including statistical significance. For 1 increase in log(GDP), life expectancy increases by 0.06422 years. Americas had 7 more years of LE than africa. Life e is strongly related to wealth.

    • Which continent is the âreferenceâ continent? the one thatâs now shown as coefficient: in this case Africa

    • What does the âyearâ coefficient represent? my model didnât have year as a predictor, but if year is included in the model, the year coefficient would represent the average increase in life expectancy per year, holding GDP and continent constant.but it also could mean technical progress over time that benefits LE independent of economic growth.

    • What do the coefficients on each continent represent? Do these make intuitive sense? how much would model shift from reference continent

  • Does a linear model seem like a good way to approach these data? Why or why not? not sure if a linear model capture demographic transition, where diminishing return is captured
